    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nWhen using `vim.fn.jobstart()` with `term = true`, special shell characters like `&` in command arguments are being interpreted by the shell, even when passing arguments as a list (which should bypass shell interpretation).\n\nvim.fn.jobstart({'npx', '-y', 'qrcode-terminal', 'hello&world'}, {term = true})\n\nThe scanned QR code only contains `hello` (the `&world` part is lost)\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n\n1. Start Neovim with minimal config:\n   ```bash\n   nvim -u NONE\n   ```\n\n2. Execute the following command:\n   ```vim\n   :=vim.fn.jobstart({'npx', '-y', 'qrcode-terminal', 'hello&world'}, {term = true})\n   ```\n\n3. Scan the QR code with WeChat or any QR scanner\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe scanned QR code should contain `hello&world`\n\n\n\n\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.11.4 and latest\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nwin11\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nwezterm\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nscoop install neovim",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "does not mean the bug is in Nvim. when i run:\n\n    lua =vim.fn.jobstart({'echo', 'hello & world'}, {term = true})\n\n\ni see:\n\n    hello & world\n\n\n\n> special shell characters like `&` in command arguments are being interpreted by the shell\n\nif that were true, then my example above would yield:\n\n    hello\n    /bin/bash: line 1: world: command not found\n\nbut i did not try on Windows.\nwhat is your 'shell'?",
